column4: Original_notes
cassava
cassava the main food - but fished & hunted, fruit important, staple is the crab (Rouse 1948: 550); plant melon, manioc, potatoes, corn, peas. But so much grows naturally (Rosny 1886: 280)
cultivate a plot for a few years & then leave it (de la Borde 1886: 241); cultivated until house site is abandoned for death or defecation (Rosny 1886: 280)
Rouse (1948b: 551) says carib cultivation similar to Arawak who build up mounds.
They think the white man's custom of fertilizing with manure is disgusting (Taylor 1938: 119); just wood ash (Taylor 1938: 146)
no fences
women do all the cultivating (de la Borde 1886: 241); Taylor (1938: 119) says the work is evenly shared
The Arawak used irrigation - but then they also used urine as fertilizer
(+); carbet (village) chief supervised cultivation probably
after burying a few relatives in one house they move. Probably at least 10 years
houses clustered around the ceremonial carbet (Taylor 1951: 28); public square houses built around it in a circle (MacNutt 1912: 71)
many villages of about 20-30 houses each
big dirty house for festivities
Taylor (1938: 126) +; Rochefort ([?]: 434) - oval
roof goes all the way to the ground & must be repaired every 3-4 years
they put up woven partitions
(-); carbet divided in 2 - kitchen & sleeping quarters (Labat [?] vol. 2: 28); Houses divided up into separate rooms (Du Terte 1667: 395)
Taylor (1946: 184) - longhouse - but never mentioned by Rochefort who says they lived in family huts; dormitory for the unmarried (Taylor 1951: 28)
altar incised
no land ownership.
funeral - everyone entertained
nothing inherited
Rouse (1948b: 556) suggests that rolls of tobacco served as standard of exchange
aid in rerooffing a house repaid with food & drink
bad memories. 6 generations back is legend.
friends trade names
groom comes to live with wife & work for her family
bride cooks for groom & next day combs his hair (Taylor 1946: 184); as soon as father offers his daughter, the marriage is accomplished (Rochefort [?]: 490)
In order to reach the most respected ranks one must kill an Arawak and be very brave in battle. Then can be a chief etc.
a wealthy person is respected because he is the bravest - not because of his wealth
slave, commoner, chiefs
slaves must wear their hair short
the chiefs & their families wear a special pendant "caracolis" made out of copper taken from raids on the mainland.
There is no limit to the number of wives. The bravest warrior is offered a couple after every successful encounter - so I suppose it's unlimited; some have 6 or 9 (de la Borde 1886: 251)
heads of households - miner chiefs bring their wives[?] to live with them.
no restrictions on hunting
The bodies of their capitains were burnt & the ashes mixed in a drink (de la Borde 1886: 253); head of carbet buried in the middle of house & house abandoned for all time (Labat [?] (vol. 4): 123)
the most prestigious, best warriors + consequently wealthiest
if he owned a negro slave then the slave is killed in order to serve him in death. - His dog also (de la Borde 1886: 252); any slave - if caught (Rochefort [?]: 512)
women & children
slave women must wear hair shorter & cannot wear traditional tiche poulou [?]
captured women are always considered slaves but their children are free.
as opposed to the Peruvians
2 main chiefs for different sides of the island
only advisory authority (Taylor 1938: 115); can hit them (Rochefort [?]: 463)
punishment left to the injured individuals
up to the individual, the society does not interfere
They seem to have been mostly from the same family but each one was elected for his virtues & ordeals
only wisdom & courage in the ordeals (Taylor 1938: 115); must have killed an enemy & be a household chief (Rochefort [?]: 464)
headmen of the longhouses (Taylor 1946: 181); community head (Rochefort [?]: 463)
all men assemble in chief's public house & debate war
chief's lieutenant, called his shadow
use a shell trumpet to announce their arrival or victory etc. with a set of different tones
the more prestigious have servants & slaves
offers a visitor huge repast comparable to the best French dinners (Rochefort ([?]: 318). Ibid p. 460 in more detail
always followed by all his household & others who wish to honor him (Rochefort [?]: 463)
He performs the puberty rites for all the children
(+); "une grande berfe de Jardinier" - a big gardener's bill?
must follow the chief around or can be slapped by him (Rochefort [?]: 463); make way for him, give complete silence (Rochefort [?]: 464)
all his possesions either buried with him or burnt. He probably had a lot- beads weapons, feathers, etc.
since he would be a warrior he would have slaves who would be killed at his death
in a hole in the house
recieves first fruits
since chief is elected as the bravest he would have the most wives; bravery is rated by number of wives
each wife has her own house
not more than anyone else, though[?]
They know no kind of pardon – just revenge
stealing considered offense against victim & punishable by death
mostly because they hate the Arawaques[?]- partly to avenge deaths in the last war, partly to attain glory
surprise attacks
special commander appointed
after war had to relinquish authority
voluntary
each household has a chief (Rochefort [?]: 463); divided into three bands Rouse 1948b: 559)
each boat had its own commander. Each island has a head chief & then sometimes the islands join together & one of the chiefs is chosen to lead them all.
parents tie their son’s dinners high up in a tree & if they wish to eat they must learn to handle the bow & arrow well enough to cut down the food.
ambush
Fled spanish in a “wedge-shaped group”
everyone supplies himself with weapons & food
a knife (de la Borde 1886: 244); only arrows & clubs (Rochefort [?]: 435)
no covering
might find the Arouques[?] palisaded, arrows do no good, so attack flaming cotton & burn the enemy into the open
wear the small bones of enemies or make flutes of them (de la Borde 1886: 247); but trophies not taken in battle (Rochefort [?]: 476)
(-); nothing much to take
only to be eaten later, the women & children become slaves
but they only eat the Arawak now, christians say give them a stomach ache (de la Borde 1886: 244); The French are the most tasty, the spanish the most tough (Rochefort [?]: 480)
a young man who has killed an enemy chief takes the chief’s name as a sign of prestige.
has to do more – but the first requirement is that he be an outstanding warrior (Rochefort [?]: 464); the bravest are offered wives on their return from the war (ibid.: 490)
only a brave warrior can submit to the tests for the head chief’s position.
(-); The cowardly will have difficulty getting a wife since no one would offer them his daughter. (Rochefort [?]: 490); They don’t go to heaven (Ober 1880: 97)
The chemeens[?]
there is a god, full of goodness, but he is so far removed that they never think of him
the brave go to a paradise where they are served by their enemies, the bad go to the paradise of the enemies to be their slaves
Cassava + beer. Offered to the devil Mboya
(-); might offer blood to Mboya
no sacrifices
each person has their own spirit & offers cassava to it at special times on a reed table set up inside the house
no priests
they have a party whatever the outcome of the war
[unreadable] a new canoe in put in the water for the first time (Rochefort [?]: 456); cutting down trees for a new house (Rouse 1948b: 560)
just the wood charms around their necks
the shamans give answers by consulting bones wrapped in cotton
they have no temples nor altars
tobacco.
shamans, they cure & divine
shamans must fast rigorously. All their fasts rigorous – 15 days without eating, normal
young boys dedicated to be either soldiers or shamans. Those to be shamans are apprenticed to respected shamans & fast etc.
no temples
carried over from the mainland caribs – if made by callinago then made on mainland (Lovén 1935: 249); men paint pots (Rosny 1886: 303)
made by the mainland caribs
for their beer
Arawak had them
little wood devil charms (Rochefort [?]: 421); carved statues (MacNutt 1912: 71)
myth of white god directing them to take stones from the beach to cut down trees (Rochefort [?]: 428); process of making stone hatchet (Rosny 1886: 282)
hammocks
spin on their thighs[?] (de la Borde 1886: 242); had spindle (Taylor 1938: 133)
(-!); Rosny (1886: 301) describes women pulling thread over & under rtv.
plain white cloth
Long loin cloth
dye reeds & cloth (Rosny 1886: 302); dye hamacs red with the same pigment they use to color themselves & black designs (Labat [?] (vol. 2): 14)
Rosny (1886: 301) calls it painting but can survive rain
copper rare even for Maya
Lovén (1935: 472) traces advent of gold to Puerto Rico through the lesser Antilles; caracoli – mixture of silver, copper & gold? (Labat [?](vol. 2): 8)
carnelian
dug out canoes
sides of the canoe built up with planks but basic hull made of hollowed log.
paddles
smaller boats have 2 masts, larger have three
steering [arrow pointing at]
“undershot prow” serves as a keel (Taylor 1951: 32); had keels (Rouse 1948b: 553)
Beyond 20 they say “much”
Rattles & conch horn
boiled cassava beer
